<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
    @make_header OpenPCells Documentation
    <body>
        @make_topbar Virtuoso Interface User Guide
        <details open>
            <summary>Introduction</summary>
            <p>
            This guide shows the features of the openPCells virtuoso interface.
            </p>
        </details>
        <details open>
            <summary>Overview</summary>
            <p>
            The openPCells project offers an interface to access the 'opc' command-line utility from within cadence virtuoso.
            This is mostly a convenience interface, as it does not offer features beyond regular opc capabilities, but only a call wrapper.
            In general the interface works by offering menu options to open script files and place figure groups with properties which represent opc objects in virtuoso.
            When opc is invoked (in various ways, as explained below), the proper commands are assembled, opc is called on the resulting file(s) and a SKILL representation (via the SKILL export module) of the layout is created.
            This in turn is loaded by virtuoso, which puts the shapes in the layout editor window from where the commands are executed.
            This is the basis for generation functions of the virtuoso interface, additionally some debugging and configuration functions are available.
            </p>
        </details>
        <details>
            <summary>Installation</summary>
            <p>
            The installation is done via a menu trigger which adds a menu to the top bar in the layout editor.
            A sample cdsinit file is given in <code>interface/virtuoso/cdsinit.il.sample</code>.
            The content of this file should be copied into the user's cdsinit (with adapted paths).
            When the cdsinit is (re-)loaded, the next invocation of the layout editor will have the 'OpenPCells' menu available.
            A successfull installation can be checked by the presence of the menu and then the invocation of the 'About' menu entry, which should show a message about openPCells and it's version.
            </p>
        </details>
        <details>
            <summary>Functions</summary>
            <p>
            The following list shows an overview of the offered interface functions:
            </p>
            <ul class="description-list">
                <li>
                    About
                    <p>
                    Display the version and some information about the openPCells project.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    Documentation
                    <p>
                    Display the version and some information about the openPCells project.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    Settings
                    <p>
                    Open the settings form to influence how opc is called, enable debugging options, modify opc group names etc.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    Configuration File
                    <p>
                    Open an editor to edit the configuration file.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    File Display
                    <p>
                    Display various files from openPCells invocations:
                    Parameter files, log files, dprint output, generated output files and exported layout files.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    Design (Top Cell)
                    <p>
                    Modify and generate design-related files.
                    This concerns the entire layout cell and is to be used with care:
                    A successfull opc call deletes <em>all</em> objects in a layout cell, whether or not they come originally from opc.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    Sub Cell
                    <p>
                    Modify and create sub-cells.
                    These functions are similar to the design files, but only concern sub-cells in the current layout cell.
                    These functions are safer to use, as they only modify groups previously generated by opc (unless malisciously crafted to look like an opc cell).
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    Power Grid
                    <p>
                    Generate a power grid via a power grid script.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    Filling
                    <p>
                    Generate filling via a fill script.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    Export
                    <p>
                    Export the current layout cell to an opc-based representation.
                    (The hierarchical export is currently broken, this function creates a flat representation.)
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </details>
        <details>
            <summary>Settings</summary>
            <p>
            The settings form allows to customize various things of the openPCells virtuoso interface.
            </p>
            <table>
                <tr>
                    <td>&nbsp;</td>
                    <td>Knocky</td>
                    <td>Flor</td>
                    <td>Ella</td>
                    <td>Juan</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Breed</td>
                    <td>Jack Russell</td>
                    <td>Poodle</td>
                    <td>Streetdog</td>
                    <td>Cocker Spaniel</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Age</td>
                    <td>16</td>
                    <td>9</td>
                    <td>10</td>
                    <td>5</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Owner</td>
                    <td>Mother-in-law</td>
                    <td>Me</td>
                    <td>Me</td>
                    <td>Sister-in-law</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <td>Eating Habits</td>
                    <td>Eats everyone's leftovers</td>
                    <td>Nibbles at food</td>
                    <td>Hearty eater</td>
                    <td>Will eat till he explodes</td>
                </tr>
            </table>
        </details>
        <details>
            <summary>Design</summary>
            <p>
            The design menu features the following entries: &quot;Edit Design&quot;, &quot;Update Design (Hierarchical)&quot;, &quot;Update Design (Flat)&quot; and &quot;Delete Design File&quot;.
            </p>
            <p>
            The edit-design entry opens the configured editor (see the section about settings) with the design file (initially empty).
            The design file is a cellscript that is directly executed by opc.
            The resulting layout is then imported into the current layout cell in virtuoso.
            </p>
            <p>
            The cellscript can be used in two ways: hierarchical and flat, whereas the only difference between the two is that opc is invoked with the <code>--flat</code> option.
            However, the hierarchical option is to be used with care, as it can be quite destructive.
            It does not only overwrite the current layout cell but all sub-cells that are being instantiated.
            Which cells are overwritten depends on the content of the opc layout and the names of all the sub-cells.
            In general it is recommended to use the flat generation.
            </p>
        </details>
        <details>
            <summary>Sub-Cells</summary>
            <p>
            The sub-cell menu assists in creating figure groups that behave like parametric cells in virtuoso.
            Just as within openPCells, two types of opc sub-cells exist: cells and cellscript cells.
            Cells store the parameters directly as properties, whereas cellscript cells are based upon a cellscript.
            Both have their uses, the use of cellscripts allows for better support for some more obscure parameter types and (as in openPCells) more complex layouts with multiple cells are possible.
            </p>
            <p>
            With the sub-cell menu these cells can be created.
            When creating a non-cellscript cell, the creation dialog prompts for a cell name (the name of an opc cell, such as <code>basic/mosfet</code> and a name for the group (arbitrary).
            For cellscripts a group name must be provided, and optionally a template name of an opc cell can be given, whereupon the cellscript is based (see the opc option <code>--template</code>).
            Automatic templates (<code>--template-auto</code>) can be enabled with the boolean radio button.
            The template field can be left blank.
            </p>
            <p>
            When a sub-cell is created, a group with a box in the 'info' layer, which can be configured with the settings form.
            This can be placed by clicking somewhere.
            The sub-cell then must be updated with the menu entry &quot;Update Sub-Cell&quot;, which will call opc with the right settings and load the shapes into the group.
            Sub-cells are always flat.
            </p>
        </details>
        <details>
            <summary>Power Grid</summary>
            <p>
            The power grid menu allows for fast creation of complex power grids.
            It is based on a power grid script, which should create the shapes.
            It is a regular cellscript, so it is expected to return an object.
            When a new power grid script is created, a template is used, which can be modified according to the layout cell.
            This template is usually a good starting point.
            </p>
            <p>
            As the power grid script typically places shapes on layers that are already present, the current layout is exported as an opc representation.
            This representation can be loaded in the power grid script and net shapes and shape outlines as excludes can be gathered from the cell.
            The default setup of the power script takes care of these things already.
            </p>
            <p>
            There are many options and possibilities for power grid creation.
            In order to keep this guide short, only the necessary modifications will be discussed.
            </p>
            <p>
            The default power grid script places alternating horizontal and vertical power strips on given nets.
            Therefore, the metal numbers (<code>hmetal</code> and <code>vmetal</code>), the strip size and spacing (<code>pwidth</code> and <code>pspace</code>) as well as the power nets (<code>powernets</code>) must be given.
            Additionally, a target area is defined as a rectangular shape.
            Currently only rectangular power grids are possible in openPCells, although it is possible to use additional excludes to limit the placement.
            The power grid script assembles excludes from the given shapes in the existing layout, enlarged by a given offset (<code>hoffset</code> and <code>voffset</code> for the horizontal and vertical lines).
            </p>
            <p>
            The power grid script can also contact existing net shapes.
            For this, the connectivity needs to be set correctly on the respective shapes and to the same net names as given in the power grid script.
            Additionally, which shapes on which layers are to be connected can be controlled by the <code>targetmetals</code> variable.
            Here, metal indices are expected, not proper layers.
            </p>
            <p>
            The power grid script tries to take care of various use cases.
            It is not necessary to use both horizontal and vertical lines, but one metal must be at least defined (one can be <code>nil</code>). 
            Furthermore, the script can also be used for preliminary virtual power connections by label (shorted by the LVS), as a means of prototyping and debugging.
            </p>
            <p>
            The power grid shapes are placed in a figure group called opcpowergrid.
            When re-running the power grid script, this group is first removed so that it is not included in the cell export.
            This makes it possible to continuously refine the power grid script without having to manually remove any shapes.
            Besides this, a menu option exists for removal of the power grid shapes (which simply removes the group) and the power grid script itself (which is then lost).
            </p>
        </details>
        <details>
            <summary>Filling</summary>
            <p>
            The fill menu allows for fast creation of filling.
            It is based on a fill script, which should create the shapes.
            It is a regular cellscript, so it is expected to return an object.
            When a new fill script is created, a template is used, which can be modified according to the layout cell.
            This template is usually a good starting point.
            In this, the fill script is very similar to the power grid script, but simpler, as it does not require any net information.
            </p>
        </details>
        <details>
            <summary>Export</summary>
            <p>
            The export entry creates an opc representation of the current layout.
            It is used by the power grid and fill generation routines and can be used by the user to export the layout to opc for modification.
            Typically it is not really needed by itself and mostly provided as a debugging option.
            The exported file can easily be viewed by the respective menu entry in the settings/file section.
            </p>
        </details>
        @include footer.html
    </body>
</html>
